title.narrative: 5.2 VULNERABLE GIRLS AND BOYS HAVE ACCESS TO AND USE WATER & SANITATION SERVICES

description.narrative: Vulnerable girls and boys, including those with disabilities, have access to, and use, adequate, safe, affordable and sustainable water and sanitation services, which contributes to Climate Change, Disaster Risks And Envionmental Degradation, Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices, Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Systems And Empowerment Of Communities. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Innovation, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Vulnerable people have access to safe drinking water, clean environment, and key hygiene/water conservation practices.

description.narrative: More than 268,269 people (155,500 children, including 217,564 females) were reached with improved access to water and sanitation in 2021. UNICEF continued to support 117,000 Syrians (67,040 children – 57,330 females) in refugee camps with life-saving WASH services. Interventions improving water/sanitation continued in vulnerable communities. Prior to school reopening, WASH facilities in 25 schools were rehabilitated, targeting 13,248 students (7,745) in vulnerable communities, creating an improved learning environment. A “Cash for WASH” initiative was piloted in ITS, providing cash transfers for the installation of water tanks and latrines and purchases of hygiene items reaching 9,789 beneficiaries (4,958 females). | Status:On-track | As-of Date:08/12/2021
